  "summary": [
    "The central deliberation question is whether the product-quality case for Marcellus at Rs 3 Cr justifies accepting three simultaneous mandate-boundary gaps and continuing a wrapper-accumulation pattern, or whether the structural signature requires sizing the action to the architecture rather than to the product. The product itself reads cleanly across every evaluation lens: Marcellus has a stable team, consistent investment style, fee structure within the PMS band, and a look-through book of high-ROCE, wide-moat businesses. Macro supports moving capital out of compressed-yield FDs into equity at this point in the rate cycle. The friction is architectural rather than transactional. Post-action equity rises to 71.7 percent against a 70 percent ceiling, debt falls to 13.3 percent against a 20 percent floor, and single-position concentration reaches 16.7 percent against a 15 percent standard ceiling. These three G1 boundaries print as simultaneous gaps, and the evidence suggests the Rs 3 Cr ticket was anchored on available FD reserve (56 percent of the block) rather than on mandate headroom.",
    "The Risk Assessor's stress testing confirms that the action does not break under any single scenario but degrades meaningfully under compound stress. Equity at the ceiling leaves zero headroom for upward market drift; a 15 percent equity rally pushes the ceiling gap to 5 percentage points without any new household action. The FMCG cycle softness flagged by the product evaluation (earnings at 6.8 percent against a 10-year average of 11.4 percent) compounds with the strategy's 35.8x trailing P/E premium; a 15-20 percent multiple compression in the 41 percent FMCG sleeve translates to roughly 6-8 percent strategy-level drawdown independent of broad market. Liquidity reserve compression drops the household below its revealed 30 percent reserve pattern (from approximately 30 percent to 18 percent of liquid AUM) at a single decision point without a stated reserve-policy revision. The Devil's Advocate and Counterfactual Engine converge on a structural read: the three-boundary signature is not a marginal clarification but evidence that the ticket was sized against product attractiveness rather than against the architecture the household has already committed to in its stated mandate. A Rs 2.0-2.2 Cr ticket would hold equity at the ceiling with marginal drift headroom, preserve debt above floor, keep single-position concentration at or below 15 percent, and still redirect roughly 40 percent of the FD reserve into the wrapper.",
    "A second structural dimension compounds the mandate-fit question. The household acquires sophistication-tier wrappers through ambient peer-network signals rather than through deliberate portfolio design, and the proposed action moves the wrapper count from one PMS to two PMS with style overlap to the existing growth-quality mandate without a stated differentiation thesis. The Risk Assessor flags this as the principal unquantifiable risk in the bundle and notes the household has not stress-tested its own architecture. The Counterfactual Engine surfaces five alternative paths that address the sizing, sequencing, and wrapper-architecture friction without abandoning the underlying conviction: ticket recalibration to Rs 2.0-2.2 Cr, staged two-tranche deployment with a 6-9 month mandate review gate, hybrid PMS-plus-quality-MF substitution, existing PMS consolidation before new wrapper deployment, and reserve-preserving partial deployment capped at Rs 1.8-2.0 Cr. The committee's deliberation turns on whether the product-fit case is strong enough to absorb the mandate-architecture gaps as accepted headroom usage, or whether the structural signature warrants sizing the action to the architecture before sizing it to the opportunity."
